const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'How much does a GEO programme cost?',
    a: 'GEO programme costs vary significantly by scope, starting point, and competitive intensity. A standalone GEO audit is typically the most efficient first investment, establishing a baseline before committing to ongoing spend. Ongoing monthly programmes range from focused monitoring-and-content retainers to comprehensive managed programmes covering audit, content production, entity management, and reporting. The figures that matter are specific to your programme — contact GEOoptimised for a scoped proposal rather than relying on industry averages that may not reflect your situation.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What are the main cost drivers in a GEO budget?',
    a: 'The four main GEO cost drivers are: (1) audit and baseline — the depth of the initial citation and entity analysis; (2) content production — the volume and complexity of pages required to build topical authority; (3) entity management — the work required to resolve and maintain consistent entity signals across platforms; and (4) monitoring and reporting — the tooling and analyst time needed to run measurement cycles. Each driver scales with the breadth of your programme and the competitive density of your target queries.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Should GEO budget come from the SEO budget or a separate line?',
    a: 'GEO budget is most commonly allocated from the SEO or broader organic marketing budget, since the disciplines share content, technical, and authority-building workstreams. However, the monitoring, entity management, and AI-platform-specific optimisation components of GEO are genuinely new activities with no SEO equivalent, which means simply reallocating existing SEO spend without increasing total budget often means neither discipline is resourced adequately. The cleanest approach is to treat GEO as a distinct investment category that grows over time as ROI evidence accumulates.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the minimum viable GEO investment?',
    a: 'The minimum viable GEO investment is an audit: a structured review of your current citation frequency, entity consistency, content extraction quality, and technical accessibility for AI crawlers. An audit produces a prioritised remediation plan. Without it, any content or entity spend is allocated on assumptions rather than evidence. After the audit, the minimum ongoing investment is monthly monitoring and the content or entity corrections the audit identified as highest priority.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How long before a GEO investment shows measurable results?',
    a: 'Citation frequency improvements from content and entity changes are typically measurable within 60 to 90 days of implementation. AI referral traffic growth follows citation frequency improvements with a lag of one to two months. Entity authority improvements compound over six to twelve months. Set measurement cadences accordingly: early monthly check-ins on citation frequency, quarterly reviews of traffic and business impact.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Should you start GEO with an audit or jump straight to content production?',
    a: 'Start with an audit. Producing content before auditing your current position means you do not know which queries you are already close to ranking for, which pages need entity corrections rather than new content, or which technical issues are preventing AI crawlers from accessing your existing pages. An audit typically reveals that a substantial share of the most impactful improvements can be achieved by correcting existing pages and entity signals — not by creating new content.',
  },
